						div(class="panel-heading")
							h3(class="panel-title") Gear ratios
						div(class="panel-body") Some of the common uses of gears are increase or decrease rotation speed, increase or decrease torque, and to change the rotation direction. Rather than randomly trying different gear combinations, we can mathematically determine the gears to use to accomplish our desired result. 
							
							p <br/> Using this <strong>Gear ratio</strong> we can calculate the number of rotations that we can create or reduce. 
							div( class="alert alert-info") <strong> Mathematics tip:</strong> The <strong>gear ratio</strong> is determined by dividing the number of teeth of the driving gear by the number of teeth in the driven gear. 
							p Two terms are relevent here: <strong>Gearing Up</strong> and <strong>Gearing Down</strong>. These result in either increasing speed or increasing torque. Torque, or power, is <strong>inversely proportional</strong> to speed. Meaning that an increase in speed results in a decrease in power. 
			div(class="row")
				div(class="col-md-12")
					div(class="panel panel-default")
						div(class="panel-heading")
							h3(class="panel-title") Gearing up
						div(class="panel-body") To increase speed and reduce torque use a large drive gear coupled to a smaller driven gear. In the example below we use a 40 tooth drive gear to turn smaller gears to get the illustrated gear ratios.So the 8 tooth gear will turn 5 complete rotations for the every rotation of the 40 tooth gear. The motor has been geared up.
							img(src="/images/gears/increasespeed.jpg")
			div(class="row")
				div(class="col-md-12")
					div(class="panel panel-default")
						div(class="panel-heading")
							h3(class="panel-title") Gearing down
						div(class="panel-body") To reduce speed and increase torque use a small Lego gear turning a larger gear. For the 40 tooth gear in this example the gear ratio is 8/40, or 1/5. This gear ratio can also be written as 40:8 or 5:1.So for every five rotations of the 8 tooth gear, the 40 tooth gear will have turned only once. The motor has been geared down.
							img(src="/images/gears/decreasingspeed.jpg")
							p Notice that you can combine gears in a chain or series to achieve different gear ratios. The gear ratio of a gear chain is calculated by multiplying the successive ratio of drive gears divided by driven gears. Here that would be: (8/20*20/24= 160/480=1/3 or 3:1)
